十九世紀音樂與美術的關聯



　
十九世紀音樂與美術的關聯




Arts  
and Humanities



音樂與美術


n           
 Terms such as color,  
harmony, texture, line, and intensity are commonly used to describe both music  
and art, but the relationship between these two subjects drew a great deal of  
attention during the nineteenth century. This led to a reevaluation of the  
nature of both music and painting and collaboration between the two arts. 


Carl Friedrich 
Zelter

n           
wrote in 1783, There is only one art---  
Zelter (1783)


n           
不但要知道不同的範疇, 並要懂得從另一邊, 另一角度來看會是怎麼樣


n           
畫家畫出有音樂性的繪畫, 作曲家以音符作畫


n           
“There is only one Art; painting and music are 
only different fields, part of this general Art; one must know the boundaries, 
but also how it looks form the other side; yes, the painter who is musical, just 
as the composer who paints, these are the true, genuine artists…


n           
十九世紀美學的發展, 逐漸形成音樂與美術前所未有的共生的關係


n           
Debussy Gauguin


n           
靠著相互的交流, 豐富, 再造他們的藝術 


Boudelaire 
 

 



n           
They lent each other new power--



十八世紀觀念


n           
 During the eighteenth century Enlightenment,  
music was perceived as an entertainment that failed when it came to reasoned  
thought. Composers were limited to pieces performed in churches or royal courts  
where music played the role of background music for social interactions 


n           
 Mozart: 小夜曲, K 185


n           
 In 1790, Emmanuel Kant dismissed music as “least amongst the fine arts, 藝術的末流because  
it plays merely with emotions”  
and “communicates by means of mere sensations  
without concepts.”  
In his opinion, the other arts “greatly  
excel[led] it, for they freely stimulate[d] the play of the imagination in a way  
that is suited to the intellect” 


十八世紀觀念


n           
 Composers  
sought to bring elements found in the visual arts and literature into their  
music, and thus elevate its status. Painters also took their lead from  
literature. From this trend came the term ut pictura poesis, or, “As  
with painting, so with poetry.” History painting  
reigned supreme, and painters like David worked on themes taken from the written  
word in the form of plays, epic poems, and historical texts. 


 

Jacques-Louis David
n    
"Oath of  
the Horatii",





十九世紀觀念Romantic  
doctrine 


 



n    
黑格爾(Hegel,  
1770-1831)、諾瓦利斯(Novalis,  
1772-1801)、蒂克(Tieck,  
1773-1853)、霍夫曼(Hoffmann,  
1776-1822)、奧古斯特•威廉•施勒格爾(August  
Wilhelm Schlegel, 1767-1845)和弟弟費德利希(Friedrich,  
1772-1829)等為當時的文壇要角，他們在自己的著作中揭示新的觀念，並認為音樂優於其他的藝術領域


n    
music was now  
valued for its vague indeterminate content, previously regarded as its greatest  
weakness


 



十九世紀觀念
n    
The most indefatigable proselytizer of instrumental music was Hoffmann,  
whose 1810 review of Beethoven's Fifth Symphony, considered to be the  
quintessential document of Romantic theory, was itself a polemic for the  
supremacy of instrumental over vocal music:
“Beethoven’s music  
presses the levers of terror, of fear, of dread, of pain, and awakens the  
endless longing that is the nature of romanticism. 


E.T.A. Hoffmann  
(1776-1822)



n    
Beethoven is a truly romantic composer (and precisely because of that, a  
truly musical one,) which may explain why he is less successful with vocal  
music, which does not permit indefinite longing…” 


n    
Musicians and  
visual artists alike began to reject the rational, classical ideal of beauty,  
and instead emphasized creative freedom


n    
Music became  
valued for what had previously been considered its greatest weakness— vagueness and obscurity. 器樂Instrumental music (without vocals free of literary influence) became the  
most valued because it communicated without the use of the spoken or written  
words. 



Ludwig Tieck蒂克
 (1773-1853)


n    
“Art 
is independent and free in instrumental music; it prescribes its own rules all 
by itself…it 
completely follows its dark drives and expresses with its triflings what is 
deepest and most wonderful…[the] 
sounds which art has miraculously discovered and pursues along the greatest 
variety of paths…do not imitate and do not beautify; rather, they constitute a separate 
world for themselves”



n    
Concert  
attendees became listeners instead of participants as concert hall lights were  
dimmed and silence maintained in order to achieve a moment of “spiritual transcendence.”精神的超脫  
Museums would later come to resemble concert halls in their “imposed  
tone of hushed reverence” . 


n    
As painters  
shifted their attention from literature to music, ut pictura poesis was replaced  
with ut pictura musica, or, “As with  
music, so with painting,”.  



十九世紀觀念 
ut pictura musica


n    
German Romantic  
painters began to favor landscapes because their forms were considered to hold a deeper meaning instead of  
representing material objects


n    
 Runge  
described landscape painting as an abstract art, and Friedrich “came  
close to painting musical ‘nothingness’  
in his Monk by the Sea” . 



Caspar David Friedrich1774-1840] 



十九世紀觀念

大自然
n    
With growing  
industrialization, artists became more attracted to nature, and landscape  
painting flourished. Musicians also felt a kinship with nature and found  
inspiration within it. Haydn’s  
Seasons and Beethoven’s Pastoral Symphony were followed by Mendelssohn’s overtures,  
Schumann’s  
Spring and Rhenish Symphonies, and the music of Berlioz, Liszt, Weber, and  
Wagner 


n    
Beethoven’s Pastoral Symphony were followed by  
 

　




n    
Mendelssohn’s overtures, 


n    
  Die  
Hebriden (Fingal's Cave), Op. 26  
  
Schumann’s Spring and Rhenish Symphonies, and the music of Berlioz, Liszt, Weber, and Wagner 



十九世紀觀念

大自然
n    
Turner


n    
Whether  
composers were inspired by landscape paintings, the landscape itself, or poetic  
descriptions of nature is difficult to determine. 


十九世紀觀念

總體藝術
n    
Many painters  
made plans to combine images with sound. This cooperation between the arts is  
called synesthesia and led to efforts to create a universal artwork, or  
Gesamtkunstwerk. 


n    
Runge hoped to  
see his drawings, The Times of Day, displayed in a cathedral-like setting and  
accompanied by music. 


n    
Runge


總體藝術
n    
Runge


十九世紀觀念

總體藝術
n    
Moritz von  
Schwind planned a series of paintings that would be displayed in a room where  
Schubert would play his compositions. These paintings represent poetry that  
had inspired Schubert’s  
music. 


十九世紀觀念

總體藝術
n    
Moritz von  
Schwind planned a series of paintings that would be displayed in a room where  
Schubert would play his compositions. These paintings represent poetry that had  
inspired Schubert’s  
music. 



比較
n    
No greater indication of change in the status of music can be found than  
by comparing the remarks on concerts and instrumental music by the  
eighteenth-century aesthetician Johann Georg Sulzer with those of Arthur  
Schopenhauer. 


n    
In 1793 Sulzer wrote: "In the last [lowest in artis­tic ranking] position we place the application of music  
to concerts, which are presented merely as entertainments, and perhaps for  
practice in play­ing.  
To this category belong concertos, symphonies, sonatas, and solos. which generally present a lively and not unpleasant noise, or  
a civil and entertaining chatter, but not one that engages the heart.  
. 


n    
Thirty years later Schopenhauer observed that "a man who gives  
himself up entirely to the impression of a symphony experiences the metaphysical."




Schopenhauer



n    
Through Schopenhauer's writings music became a superstar as it emerged  
from Kant's earlier banishment to occupy an elite position within a  
philosophical system. Schopenhauer provided a theoretical explanation and  
justification for Romantic intuitions about music's unique nature 


Wagner



n    
His music was impressive because it achieved what  
Romantic art had been striving for—a state of ecstasy that was sensuous and  
mystical. One artist who was profoundly affected by Wagner’s  
music was Fantin-Latour. His Around the Piano, exhibited at the 1885 Salon, was  
a tribute to the friends that he listened to Wagner’s  
music with. He also produced a series of lithographs inspired by Wagner’s  
operas. These were not merely illustrations of the stories, but through his  
energetic sharp lines and dense tonalities represented visual equivalents to the  
emotions expressed by the Wagner’s  
music


Wagner, Fantin


n    
The Rhine Gold 
06. Entry  
Of The Gods Into Valhalla     07:14  





 



Debussy



n    
Claude-Achille Debussy was one composer who was  
influenced by this emphasis on color. His compositions led to a new style of  
musical impressionism, a style that created descriptive impressions through rich  
and varied timbres and harmonies. This was accomplished through the use of  
suggestive titles, reminisces of natural sounds, and dance rhythms  
Interestingly, Debussy was more interested in the paintings of Whistler and  
Turner than in those of the Impressionists


 


Debussy


n    
Nocturne in Blue in Silver, whose themes were actually about color. It  
was from Whistler that Debussy used the title


 



Debussy


n    
02. Nuages    
07:33   
03. Fetes  
  06:58   
04. Sirenes  
 12:44


Whistler



n    
Whistler: Harmony in Green and Rose: The Music  
Room 1860-61


Whistler



n    
Whistler: Symphony in White Number 1: The White Girl 1862



共(通感)應 
synesthesia 


n     
By the end of the nineteenth century, synesthesia reached its height,  
with artists from Debussy to Gauguin enhancing and restructuring their art  
through mutual exchange. This led to twentieth century abstraction in music, and  
nonobjective subject matter in painting. As Charles Baudelaire observed, the  
arts “len[t]  
each other new powers.” The events of the nineteenth century led to阿波利奈爾Apollinaire’s(1880∼1918)prediction  
of the modernism that would become prevalent in the twentieth century. “Thus we are heading towards an entirely new form of art  
which will be to painting (such has been conceived until now) what music is to  
literature. It will be a pure painting, in the same manner that music is pure  
literature


 






